{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_ironsprings_ver01/data/sn84020064/00414217709/1927033001/0718.xml":{"full_text":"SIX\nSTRONG BACKING\nSENDS RAILS TO\nNEW HIGH POINT\n(By the Associated Press)\nStock market averages:\nDate 20 Industrials 20 Kails\nTuesday 148.70 136.57\nMonday 148.92 136.91.\nWeek ago 146.39 133.47\nYear agu 123.11 105.88\nHigh, 1927 151.85 137.45\nLow, 1927 141.23 125.5 S\nTotal stock sales 1,906,700 shares.\nNEW YORK, March 29 (IP). \u2014Irregu\nlarities in price movement developed\nin today's stock market, but powerful\nfinancial interests sponsoring a group\nof high priced rails and* industrials\nnevertheless succeeded in marking\nthem up to high records. Final quota\ntions disclosed a fairly long list of\n1 to 5 point gains, interspersed with a\nsmall number of net declines of a simi\nlar character.\nU. S. Steel common touched a new\ntop at 166%; General Motors at 183%;\nCommercial Solvents B at 298%; Dela\nware and Hudson at 199%; Baltimore\nand Ohio at 115%, and Rock Island at\n88%. Other highs included Dupont,\nAll American Cables, International\nTelephone, R. H. Macy, Hayes Wheel,\nRemington Typewriter, Underwood\nTypewriter, Woolworth and several\nothers.\nOn the other hand, American Brown\nBoveri, Electric Refrigeration, Dodge\nBrothers A and the preferred and the\nWilson company issues sank to new\nlow levels for the year, but the sell\ning was believed to reflect special\nsituations within the companies in\nvolved.\nReduction of over $38,000,000 in\nbrokers\u2019 loans last week had a bullish\neffect on speculative sentiment. Wall\nstreet also was inclined to the belief\nthat the strength of the high-priced\nissues represented pure investment\nbuying, attracted by the fact that cur\nrent yields even at the prevailing high\nquotations were better than on most\nhigh-grade bonds. With indications\nthat $400,000,000 will be distributed\naround the end of the month in the\nform of dividends, interest and bond\nredemptions, it is considered logical to\nassume that at least part of these!\nFOR REAL ECONOMY\nBuy Something Made of\nCopper\nCalumet Arizona\nMining Company\nDouglas, Arizona\nThe\nMoctezuma Copper\nCompany\u2019s\nStore Department\nIMPORTERS, JOBBERS AND RETAILERS IN\nGENERAL MERCHANDISE\nQUOTATIONS UPON APPLICATION\nNacozari, Sonora, Mexico\nMUTT AND JEFF That\u2019s a Good One On Augustus Mett, Esquire. i B By BUD FISHER\nYbut mutt you shootA right fx. Don't wa'mtV\"/woofs? i mcvigp?\nA DAfcM good GAMG at ThATI I AnV sTfcoKesi of A HANjDvCAP ffc A jAAIPfI\noF golf AMD X\u2019/VA HOOJ MAMY f GIVG MG of WOOFS But j 1 Afflf ||Tl B 5L*\nAWfGfti i'b Be- ST*OKC-S THtsee Guess it's all sight. iffWiit Jr\" M OfP!\nA fool td Bc-t 'WOOFS' AMD BC-VS l ffVVI ft f\n'you FWG Bucks J Do x'll pLAV K S lhi r V. W\no I\u25a0\u25a0. .1.1 _. (Copjfij; Djf H. C. I'isher.) threat Rritaip Rights ijcaerved. Trade Mark Reg. U. S. Pat. Office\nfunds will find their way into stock\nmarket channels. Publication of sev\neral additional February railroad earn\nings reports, bringing the total to 63\nclass one carriers, brings aggregate\nnet income of these carriers last month\nabove that of the corresponding period\nlast year. A compilation of the first\nreturns made an unfavorable compari\nson, but it now appears as though the\ntotal February net of all class one car\nriers may reach $70,000,000 as against\nslightly less than $63,300,000 last year.\nRevival of activity and strength in\nthe Missouri Pacific issues was accom\npanied by rumors that plans were un\nder way ot clear up the accumulation\nof dividends on the preferred. Chesa\npeake and Ohio lost ground toddy, but\nWall street heard that an early re\nsumption of conferences between the\nVat: Sweringens and the minority in\nterests was forthcoming on the re--\nported plan of the Delaware and Hud\nson to follow the action of Lackawanna\nin segregating its treasury assets.\nCall money renewed at 4% per cent\nand held steady at that figure all day.\nThere was no change in time money,\nand commercial paper rates.\nCommodity markets displayed a\nmuch firmer undertone. Active wheat\nfutures advanced about a cent a bushel\nwith short covering- operations re\nported to represent a large share of\nthe buying. Cotton closed 15 to 23\npoints higher on buying jjpfluenced by\nreports of unfavorable weather.\nForeign exchanges were slightly re\nactionary, with demand sterling ruling\naround $4.55.% and French francs\naround 3.91 cents.\ngraiFmarket\nCHICAGO, March 29 (d 3 \u2014Evidence of\nexport transactions of unusual magni\ntude strengthened the wheat market\ntoday, although at first prices rvere in\nclined to sag. Closing quotations on\nwheat were firm, cent to 1 cent net\nhigher, with corn cent to cent up,\noats showing cent to cent gain\nand provisions varying from 10 cents\ndecline to 17 cents advance.\nThroughout the day talk was cur\nrent of big demand for ocean freight\nvessels to carry grain. The Canadian\ngrowers\u2019 pool was said to have taken\nvessel room for the shipment to Europe\nof as much as 8,000,000 bushels of\nwheat. Meanwhile premiums for num\nber 2 hard wheat at the Gulf of Mexi\nco were the highest in weeks, 10%\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH, WEDNESDAY MORNING. MARCH 30, 1927.\nBillion in Gems\nIs Dirt to Him\n\u2014NEA, 1,6 s Angeles Bureau\nAT Million dollars worth of dia\nmonds and gold is merely so much\ndirt to Major Alexander Willcox.\nThe major, arriving recently in\niLos Angeles for his first glimpse\nof America, has supervised the ex\ntraction of a billion dollars worth\n,Qt gems and precious metal from\nthe South African mines.\nPromising Business\nOutlook Followed by\nRecord Stock Prices\nNEW YORK, March 29 (A 3 )\u2014Tvven\nty-five individual stocks including a\nselect assortment of high priced\nrails and industrials sold at their\nhighest prices since 1925, or longer,\non the New York stock exchange\ntoday. The promising business out\nlook, rumors of special dividend de\nvelopments and an investment de\nmand arising* from the distribution\nof several hundred million dollars in\ndividend and interest payments\naround the end of the month, pro\nvided the back ground for the ad\nvance, but profit taking and bear\nselling in other quarters caused con\nsiderable irregularity.\nU. S. ..Steel common again headed\nthe list of new highs by touching\n166 3-4. General Motors touched a.\nlew peak at 183 1-4, Dupont at\n22i 3-4 and Commercial Solvents i\n8., at 298 1-2. Not all the gains j\nwere maintained.\ncents a bushel over Chicago May de- j\nlivery. Furtheripore, country offerings:\nin the southwest were smaller. Red j\nwheat was reported firmer in the east, j\nand the world\u2019s available supply shows*\n7,974,000 decrease for the week. Heavy)\nabandonment of wheat acreage in!\nwestern Kansas was noted by grain\ndealers, and this circumstance at\ntracted much notice, at variance with\nadvices earlier in the day pointing to j\nauspicious crop conditions generally\nbotli in this country and abroad.\nThe temporary downward trend oifi\nthe market around the opening was\nalso associated with assertions that\nmonthly unofficial domestic crop sum\nmaries to be issued after April 1 would\nindicate a large, yield. On the other\nhand, reports that Albania was mobil\nizing troops and .that Jugo-Slavia had\ngiven notice of defensive action were\neffective in emphasizing the price ral\nlies witnessed as the day drew to an\nend.\nCorn developed independent firmness\nowing to scantiness of receipts. Ship-\nping demand, from the east, however,\nremained laggard. Oats followed corn.\nProvisions were irregular, influenced\nby conflict of impulses from the hog\nmarket and from grain.\nLIBERTY BONDS\nNEW YORK, March 29 (JP). \u2014Liberty\nbonds closed:\n3%s 100.26\nFirst 4%s 103. 5\nSecond 4%s 1.. 100.13\nThird 4%s 101\nFourth 4%s 103.26\nU. S. q. 4%s 113\nCOTTON^MARKET\nNEW YORK, March 29 (A>). \u2014The gen-\neral cotton market closed barely\nsteady but from 13 to 17 points net\nhigher.\nDaily Average Crude\nOil Production Falls\nNEW YORK, March 29 (JP). \u2014The\ni daily average gross crude oil produc\ntion in the United States decreased\n1.500 barrels for the week ended March\nj 26, totaling 2,461,950 barrels, says the\nI weekly summary of the American Pot\nroleum institute today. The daily aver\nage production east of California was\nI 1,823,250 barrels, an increase of 4,400\nI barrels.\nThe daily average production in bar\nrels:\nWyoming- 60,700 Decrease 3,550\nMontana 14,600 Increase 50\nColorado 7,650 Decrease 300\nNew Mexico 4,950\nCalifornia 638,700 Decrease 5,900\nO. A- R. G. DEFERS INTEREST\nNEW YORK, March 29 (A s ).\u2014Directors\nof the Denver and Rio Grande Western\nrailroad, afte r a two-hour meeting to\nday, voted to defer payment of interest\non the general mortgage 5 per cent\ncoupon bonds. Interest on these bonds\nfrom February 1, 1924, to \"February 1,\n1929, is cumulative but need not be\npaid on due dates if net income, in the\nopinion of the directors, does not suf\nfice.\nSTOCK QUOTATIONS\nClosing Quotations Furnished by\nRICE COMPANY, Brokers,\n910 G Ave. Phone 119\nAtchison 178%\nCanadian Pacific 184\nSt. Paul 14\nSouthern Pacific 112%\nUnion Pacific ....170%\nj Missouri Pacific 53%\nNorthern Pacific 85%\nBaltimore and Ohio 115%\nReading- 109\nNew York Central 145%\nPennsylvania 59%\nKansas City Southern 51%\nAmerican Sugar 83%\nRepublic SJeel 71%\nU. S. Steel 166%\nCrucible 91\nBethlehem 53%\nVanadium 52%\nAmerican Smelting 145%\nAnaconda 46%\nMiami 15%\nInspiration 20\nGranby I 36%\nNevada Consolidated 14%\nCalumet and Arizona 67 @6B\nCerro de Pasco 62%\nKennecott 62%\nChile 36%\nGreene 37\nInternational Nickel 40%\nHowe 39%\nButte Superior 9%\nMagma 35%\nI Texas Gulf Sulphur 61\nRadio 47%\nAllied Chemical 141%\nAmerican Can 46%\nWarner Pictures 27\nGeneral Electric 85%\nA. .T. and T 166%\nGoodrich 54\nU. S. Rubbdr..?.-......... 61%\nDodge common 19%\nDodge preferred 76%\nWillys Overland 21%\nStudebaker 53%\nGeneral Motors 182%\nNash 64\nHudson 69%\nChrysler 40%\nAmerican Locomotive ....111\nBaldwin 186%\nNew York Air Brake 43%\nMarland 49%\nSinclair 17%\nTexas Company 48%\nStandard Oil of N. J 37%\nPan B 63%\nPhillips Pete 49%\nShattuck 4%@ 5\nArizona Commercial 6%@ 7\nOld Dominion 14\nVerde Extension 25% 25%\nNew Cornelia 22 22%\nBelmont I%@ 1%\nGrand Central 2 2%\nAhumada 4%\nErupcion 75 85\nVerde Central 2%\nCOPPER AND SILVER QUOTATIONS\nThe average daily quotations for\ncopper and silver, as carried by the\nEngineering and Mining Journal for\nthe week ending- March 22, are as fol\nlows: Copper, 13.16; silver, 55.69.\nA\nHawley Hawley\nShippers\u2019 Representatives\nASSAYERS, CHEMISTS\nORE BUYERS\nDouglas, Ariz. 1023 G Ave.\nEl Paso, Texas 702 Mills Bldg.\nCHERNIAVSKYS\nPRAISED HIGHLY\nBY N. Y CRITIC\nA well known New York music\ncritic, writing of the Cherniavskys,\nsays:\n\u201cThey are three young' priests from\n(lie Temple of the Muses, who have\nboen projected into the earth-world\nMOM\u2019N POP By Taylor\nGosh.x wish Yjhy dom't you ask f yoo\u2019us always j( i dowt hmus a\nPOP WOULD QIMM6 h,IU A6o \u00b0T IT? V OO ToLD ME X WAS DOWUTH THAT\nA RAISE\u2014 VIONDCR. S KMOu; m(l 2* t 5 l T iQ 6ND OT <T\n)P H 6 FKPFf\u00ae TS WTR YOU)-AMO Trte:N TYT6 (S OFFuse\nTo WoKI MY S YOU'D J MAMAG6R-YOU'LL\nTO WORK ALL MY J BETTER HURRY OR AtORG J Hf\\V\u00a3 To 56G\n--1 V* 1 j*\nall x (LAN see <m These books A wr> thzvHc tua-h J////Mk\nV IS R6DINK- EYERYTHtKKo <iO(NG THAT S THAT.\n7 OUT AND NOTHING COM\u00ab 0 <h (N-/ v\n|n= this Keeps op Much y VllWlJT\\/m\nJ 1 jt\u2019\nbv nea SERVICE. INC. j\nFRECKLES AND HIS FRIENDS ~By Blosser\nV J V6AM-BOT\nV A A)E SOM VOI'TA- AAD A/O AIR SUM- 3 /aOM R\nVOO\nDo VMim ir \\r OIZB am' i'llaaos 70 see you m x smoy some\nv, 2 /I E/00 USAsAooriM* ri/o /J zparqows vnita J\n\nI\nr TAIKABOOr S)\\OOTltf\u2019l 6 '\\maa3!! WAV )f\\{ AJosiC-l SIXOT k\nf?\n(o bring comfort to the hearts of\ntens of thousands. Their music\nbrings with it a message of hope\nand joy, that will tend to develop\nexpanding ideas in those privileged\nto hear it. One leaves the presence\nof these artists and the concert hall\nthey play in, but one never entirely\nleaves the presence of their haun*\ning music, for its essence seems to\ncling permanently to one and makes\nfor increased happiness and optim\nism. It I wanted to do a good turn\nto anyone, I would recommend them\nto listen to the Cherniavskys\u2019 music,\nand that as often as possible.\u201d\nThere has been such exceptional\ninterest evoked in these much-trav\neled artists that it is expected they'\nwill receive an enthusiastic recep\ntion on their visit here when they\nappear on the evening of March 31\nat the Grand theatre under the aus\npices of the Douglas Music club.\nScratch Pade for sale at Dispatch\nOffice.\u2014Advt.\n\nOld Newspapers in bundles for sale\nat Dispatch Office.-\u2014Advt.","height":"24888","width":"19545"}}
